obo:CHEBI_58178  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:685de18700001148
        a                 owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Normal CERT Function and Regulation:\nSphingolipids are crucial for membrane structure, signal transduction, and brain development and function, with their metabolism tightly regulated by homeostatic circuits.\nThe ceramide transporter (CERT) plays a central role in sphingolipid biosynthesis by transferring ceramide (Cer) from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) to the trans-Golgi membrane, where it is converted to sphingomyelin (SM).\nUnder normal conditions, when sufficient rates of SM production are reached, CERT is phosphorylated and undergoes a conformational change that inactivates it, leading to its redistribution from membranes to the cytosol. This phosphorylation cycle involves protein kinase D (PKD) initiating phosphorylation at p.S132, followed by CSNK1G2 (casein kinase 1 γ 1) phosphorylating other sites in the serine-rich region (SRR), and the ER phosphatase PP2Cε reversing this action." , "Automated change 2025-08-14: GO:0010707 replaced by GO:0001576" ;
        lego:modelstate   "development" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0009-0002-7487-1936" ;
        dc:date           "2026-05-12" ;
        dc:title          "De novo sphingomyelin synthesis with regulation (Human) CerS5 Recon4IMD" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://holthuis-lab-uos.de" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  obo:NCBITaxon_9606 .

